# McRPG Entity & Holder System

## Holder Hierarchy

```
AbilityHolder                  — any entity that can have abilities; the base type
  └── LoadoutHolder            — restricted to using only the abilities in their loadout
        └── SkillHolder        — also has levelable skills
```

`McRPGPlayer` is NOT a subclass of these — it composes them:

```java
public class McRPGPlayer extends CorePlayer {
    private final SkillHolder skillHolder;   // access via asSkillHolder()
    private final QuestHolder questHolder;   // access via asQuestHolder()
}
```

`QuestHolder` is a separate composition (not in the hierarchy above), currently held by `McRPGPlayer` and tracked separately in `EntityManager`.

## When to Type to Each Level

| Use case | Type to use |
|----------|-------------|
| Code that works for any entity with abilities (including mobs) | `AbilityHolder` |
| Code that requires loadout-restricted ability activation | `LoadoutHolder` |
| Code that needs skill XP / level data | `SkillHolder` |
| Code that is player-specific (settings, DB, Bukkit Player) | `McRPGPlayer` |

Avoid typing to `McRPGPlayer` unless you genuinely need player-only features. Prefer the narrowest holder type that satisfies the requirement.

## Retrieving a Holder from EntityManager

```java
EntityManager entityManager = plugin.registryAccess()
    .registry(McRPGRegistryKey.MANAGER)
    .manager(McRPGManagerKey.ENTITY);

// Any entity (player or mob) — returns AbilityHolder (may actually be SkillHolder at runtime)
Optional<AbilityHolder> holder = entityManager.getAbilityHolder(entity.getUniqueId());

// Narrow to SkillHolder when you need skill data
holder.ifPresent(h -> {
    if (h instanceof SkillHolder skillHolder) {
        // work with skills
    }
});
```

## Retrieving McRPGPlayer from a Bukkit Player

`McRPGPlayer` is a `CorePlayer`. Use the `PlayerManager` from McCore:

```java
PlayerManager<McRPGPlayer, McRPG> playerManager = plugin.registryAccess()
    .registry(RegistryKey.MANAGER)
    .manager(CoreManagerKey.CORE_PLAYER_MANAGER);

Optional<McRPGPlayer> mcRPGPlayer = playerManager.getPlayer(player.getUniqueId());
```

Then get the skill or quest holder via delegation:

```java
mcRPGPlayer.ifPresent(p -> {
    SkillHolder skillHolder = p.asSkillHolder();
    QuestHolder questHolder = p.asQuestHolder();
});
```

## AbilityHolder — Key Responsibilities

- Stores `AbilityData` per `NamespacedKey` (available abilities and their data)
- Manages cooldown expiry tasks (via `DelayableCoreTask`)
- Controls the **ready state** — `readyHolder()` / `unreadyHolder()` / `isHolderReadied()`
- Fires `AbilityHolderReadyEvent` and `AbilityHolderUnreadyEvent` on state change
- Tracks active abilities: `addActiveAbility(ability, durationSeconds)` auto-cleans up

## SkillHolder — Key Responsibilities

- Stores `SkillHolderData` per `NamespacedKey` (current level + experience)
- Fires `SkillGainExpEvent` / `PostSkillGainExpEvent` on XP gain
- Fires `SkillGainLevelEvent` / `PostSkillGainLevelEvent` on level-up
- XP gain calls are routed through `SkillHolder.gainExperience(skill, amount)`

## EntityManager — Tracking

```java
// Track a new AbilityHolder (done automatically for players on join)
entityManager.trackAbilityHolder(abilityHolder);
entityManager.removeAbilityHolder(abilityHolder);

// Track a QuestHolder separately
entityManager.trackQuestHolder(questHolder);
entityManager.removeQuestHolder(questHolder);

// Check if tracked
boolean tracked = entityManager.isAbilityHolderTracked(holder);
```

Non-player entities are registered as plain `AbilityHolder` instances (not `SkillHolder`) unless explicitly subclassed.

## Anti-Patterns

- **Do not cast `AbilityHolder` to `McRPGPlayer` directly** — always check `instanceof McRPGPlayer p` first
- **Do not store `AbilityHolder` references outside of `EntityManager`** — it owns the lifecycle; stale references won't be removed on unload
- **Do not bypass `EntityManager`** — never construct or track holders manually; let the load/unload task infrastructure handle it
- **Do not hold `SkillHolderData` references across ticks** — re-fetch from `skillHolder.getSkillHolderData(skillKey)` each time

